  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it’s something I've seen play out firsthand in my own life as a fitness trainer who’s also deeply invested in my children’s education. Growing up in a multicultural household in Naples, I’ve witnessed how stereotypes about intelligence and capability can silently undermine people’s performance. For instance, when my kids—both of whom are curious and smart—start asking questions about science, I often hear them say, 'My teacher said girls aren’t good at math,' or 'Boys are the only ones who should be in robotics.' These comments, though seemingly minor, can create a self-fulfilling prophecy where individuals internalize the belief that they don’t belong in certain fields. As a fitness trainer, I know that mindset shifts can be as powerful as physical training; if someone believes they’re not cut out for a task, they’ll stop trying. Stereotype threat is real and it’s especially harmful in STEM fields where diversity in thought is crucial. We absolutely need to address it—starting with simple, consistent messaging that everyone has the right to succeed regardless of gender, race, or background. In my community, I’ve seen programs that pair students with mentors who share their interests, which helps dismantle the fear of not belonging. It’s not about fixing people; it’s about creating environments where everyone feels seen and valued. If we don’t act now, we’ll keep losing potential talent to the cycle of self-doubt.",
